\section{Introduction} \label{sec:intro}

\subsection{Photosynthesis}

Photosynthesis is the basis of the ecosystem food chain and “the ultimate source of all of humankind’s food and oxygen” (Johnson, 2016). Oxygenic photosynthesis is a process that allows certain organisms, including plants, to harvest solar energy to synthesize organic carbon compounds, starting from carbon dioxide and water and generating oxygen as well (Arnon, 1971): 

\begin{equation}
   6H_2O + 6CO_2 + light \rightarrow C_6H_{12}O_6 + 6O_2
    \label{eq:photosynthesis}
\end{equation}

The photosynthetic processes described here concern C3 plants, and not C4 and CAM plants, which mostly live in tropical climates and have a different anatomy and different photosynthetic strategies.
\smallskip

Photosynthesis mostly takes place in the leaves. Figure \ref{fig:leaf} shows the typical anatomy of a leaf. Different cell types in the leaf contribute to the photosynthetic process: 
$CO_2$ entry is controlled by stomata in the lower epidermis, photosynthetic parenchyma (mesophyll) cells contain many chloroplasts and are the principal center of photosynthesis, whereas vascular tissues transport the sap with the necessary compounds into the leaves (xylem), or towards the rest of the plant (phloem) (Mauseth J., 2006). 
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{images/leaf.jpg}
    \caption{Representation of the cross-section of a leaf. A leaf contains a waxy cuticle, epidermal cells on its upper and lower surface, two types of mesophyll (palisade parenchyma and spongy parenchyma) and transport tissues (xylem and phloem) which are present in the vascular bundle. Figure from Diah et al., 2014.}
    \label{fig:leaf}
\end{figure}

The site of photosynthesis in the cell is the chloroplast, an organelle with two outer membranes and one thylakoid membrane. The thylakoid membrane divides the chloroplast into two spaces: the stroma on the outside and the lumen on the inside. 
\smallskip

In plants, photosynthesis can be divided into two phases: 

\begin{itemize}

\item A first light-dependent phase that happens in the thylakoid membrane. It results in the production of adenosine triphosphate  (ATP) and reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH). The energy of light is thus converted into chemical energy.

\item A second metabolic phase that happens in the stroma. Here, ATP (high-energy compound) and NADPH (high reducing power) are used by the enzymes of the Calvin-Benson cycle and $CO_2$ gets reduced and fixed into carbohydrates (Johnson, 2016). ATP and NADPH provide the 479 kJ that are necessary for photosynthesis to occur, as it is an endergonic process (Antal et al., 2013). 

\end{itemize}


\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{images/chloropl.png}
    \caption{Image of a chloroplast from a leaf of Phleum pratense, taken with an electron microscope. A system of thylakoid membranes divides a space called lumen from the external stroma. Thylakoid membranes are the site of the electron transport chain (light phase of photosynthesis). Figure from Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002}.
    \label{fig:chlor}
\end{figure}

The first phase of photosynthesis requires pigments, which in plant cells are mainly chlorophyll \textit{a} and \textit{b}, \textit{i.e.} molecules with a ring structure similar to porphyrin (Quieroz et al., 2017). When chlorophyll absorbs photons at certain wavelengths - mostly the blue (425–450 nm) and red parts (600–700 nm) of the visible spectrum -, it reaches an excited, unstable state {that cannot be maintained for long}. As the excited molecule goes back to its ground state, the extra energy can be disposed of through energy transfer to a neighboring molecule, which in turn becomes excited (Rascio et al. 2017). This is the process that happens in photosystems I and II, two complexes that can be found in the thylakoid membrane. They are formed by hundreds of pigment molecules that collect and transfer energy to a reaction center, called P680 in photosystem I and P700 in Photosystem II. Two chlorophylls in the reaction center behave differently than other pigments in the complex: instead of transferring energy, one of them undergoes oxidation, transferring an electron to the other and thus making a redox chain possible (Johnson, 2016). 
\smallskip

The electron transport chain (Figure \ref{fig:light}) involves a series of molecules that are present in the thylakoid membrane, ending with ferredoxin/ NADP+ reductase (FNR). This pathway is unidirectional, as electrons are transferred from stronger reductants to weaker ones (Arnon, 1971). As a result of the electron chain, NAPD+ is reduced to NADPH, whereas water reduces oxidized P680 back to its former state and is therefore converted to oxygen. The electron chain also causes proton transport across the membrane, with an accumulation of protons in the lumen. This gradient is used by the ATP synthase to generate ATP through phosphorylation. (Hill and Bendall, 1960 + Johnson, 2016). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/light_phase.png}
    \caption{Electron transport chain in the thylakoid membrane, with photosystem II, cythocrome $b_6f$, photosystem I, ferredoxin and FNR. The proton gradient produced by the pathway is used by ATP synthase (phosphorylation). Image from Johnson, 2016}
    \label{fig:light}
\end{figure}

After the light-dependent reactions, there is a metabolic phase: $CO_2$ is fixed into organic compounds during the Calvin-Benson cycle, which is made up of 13 reactions. Primary $CO_2$ assimilation is catalyzed by the enzyme RuBisCO (ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/ oxygenase), when the sugar ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate undergoes carboxylation. The first three reactions lead to the formation of two molecules of a triose phosphate called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P), thanks to the previously produced ATP and NADPH, which provide energy and reducing power. The other ten reactions aim at regenerating RuBP so that it can be used in the next cycle (Biel \& Fomina, 2015). In total, the cycle uses 3 molecules of ATP and 2 of NADPH to assimilate one $CO_2$ molecule (Rascio, 2017). 
\smallskip

When three $CO_2$ are fixed into six G3P molecules, five of these molecules become a part of the cycle again, by being regenerated into RuBP; the sixth molecule is converted into other compounds, such as sucrose and starch (Johnson, 2016). 


\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{images/calvin_cycle.jpg}
    \caption{The 13 reactions of the Calvin cycle. Figure from Sun at al., 2003}
    \label{fig:calvin}
\end{figure}
 

\subsection{Water potential and xylem transport}
Sap (water and minerals) is absorbed by the roots and then travels inside a vascular tissue, the xylem, throughout the root system, the stem and the leaves. In Angiosperms, the xylem is constituted by dead, elongated cells that belong to two different categories, tracheids and vessel elements. Both have lignified secondary walls and are stacked on top of one another, but vessel elements have perforated cross walls, forming a continuous tube (Venturas et al., 2017). 
\smallskip

% xylem image?
The concept of water potential, which is defined as a "measure of the free energy of water per unit volume (J $m^{-3}$)" relative to pure water in reference conditions (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002), is fundamental to explain sap transport inside the plant. Water potential can be described by equation \ref{eq:water}:

\begin{equation}
 \psi_{H_{2}O} = \mu_{H_2O}/V_{H_2O},  
 \label{eq:water}
\end{equation}

where $\mu$ is the chemical potential of water and $V_{H_2O}$ is its molar volume (Rascio, 2017). It is made up of different components, which can be summarized by equation \ref{eq:potential}:

\begin{equation}
    \psi_{H_2O} = \psi_s + \psi_p + \psi_g
    \label{eq:potential}
\end{equation}

$\psi_g$ is the gravity component, which has a minor role in small plants. $\psi_p$ is the hydrostatic pressure: when it increases, this factor causes $\psi_{H_2O}$ to get higher. Osmotic potential ($\psi_s$) describes the effect of solutes on $\psi_{H_2O}$. It becomes more negative as solutes accumulate in a plant cell, causing the water potential to also decrease. Water moves from higher to lower values  when a $\Delta\psi_{H_2O}$ is present (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). 
\smallskip

The roots can contribute directly to water uptake by generating a $\Delta\psi_{H_2O}$ between soil and root, which is caused by an osmotic gradient. As ions accumulate in the xylem, $\psi_s$ increases, and $\psi_{H_2O}$ decreases, allowing water to flow in (Gambetta et al., 2017). 

The main force that drives sap transport, however, is a pressure gradient (($\Delta\psi_p$) between leaves and roots, as the cohesion-tension theory claims. According to this theory, water in the xylem behaves like a cohesive, unbroken column that can ascend from roots to leaves because it is driven by evapotranspiration happening inside pores of leaf cell walls. Because of the hydrophilic elements in the cell wall, as the water evaporates, the meniscus becomes more concave. The concavity of the water-air interfaces inside the mesophyll cell walls creates a negative pressure (water potential), which propagates to neighboring areas, creating the driving force necessary to pull water from the soil to the evaporation site (Brown, 2013). Unless a plant is stressed due to excessive transpiration, the transpired water should be entirely replaced by the water absorbed by the roots and then transported inside the xylem (Hölttä et al., 2017).

The rate of root water uptake (Q) depends on the water potential gradient between the soil and the xylem, and on root surface area (S) (Gambetta, 2017). Hydraulic conductivity (Lp) summarizes the relationship with the following equation:

\begin{equation}
    Lp= Q/\Delta\psi*S
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{images/Hydraulic_cond.png}
    \caption{Hydraulic conductivity of a root system. The water flow rate in the root is controlled by a water potential gradient and by the root surface area. Figure from Gambetta et al., 2017}
    \label{fig:conductance}
\end{figure}

% water potential as a way to monitor plant stress (papers)
% bigger water pot gradients --> higher traspiration rate --> higher stress due to water loss 

\subsection{Stomata} \label{sec: stomata}
While the relative water vapor concentration in the mesophyll is greater than its concentration in the atmosphere, due to xylem activity, the opposite is true for $CO_2$ concentration, which is lower in the leaf (Venturas et al., 2017). These concentration gradients control water loss ($H_2O$ evapotranspiration) and $CO_2$ uptake, which are also influenced by another factor, the diffusional resistance. Thus, the transpiration rate can be calculated with the following equation:

\begin{equation}
    Tr = \frac{C_{w leaf} - C_{w air}}{R_{leaf} + R_{air}}
\end{equation}

$C_{w leaf}$ and $C_{w air}$ are the concentrations of water vapor in the leaf and in the air, while $R_{leaf}$ and $R_{air}$  represent the resistance in those same spaces (Rascio et al., 2017). 
\smallskip

In particular, $R_{leaf}$ is the leaf stomatal resistance to gas diffusion, \textit{i.e.} the resistance associated with the stomatal pores in the epidermis of leaves. Plants transpire and take up $CO_2$ through these apertures, therefore the regulation of their size is essential to make sure the plant does not lose too much water, but still gets enough $CO_2$. Thus, stomatal resistance is controlled by two guard cells that surround the pore and can sense temperature, humidity, intracellular $CO_2$ concentration and other factors. They respond by changing their turgor pressure, which leads to the opening or closing of the pores (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). % co2-evapotransp trade-off

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/Stomata_in_out.png}
    \caption{Water and $CO_2$ uptake thorugh the leaf. The concentration gradients control water loss and $CO_2$ uptake through stomatal apertures e.g. vapor content concentration in the leaf is higher than in the atmosphere. Stomata exert physical resistance to the gas diffusion.}
    \label{fig:leaf_2}
\end{figure}

Stomatal resistance is influenced by temperature. For instance, at mid to high latitudes, an increase in temperature is associated with a higher $\Delta C_w$ between the leaf and the air, and therefore to higher transpiration rates, causing an increase in stomatal resistance (Rascio et al., 2017). The rate of photosynthesis and stomatal conductance are also interconnected: with high photosynthetic activity, stomatal conductance (the inverse of stomatal resistance) is also high, but an increase in the internal leaf $CO_2$ concentration can cause an increase in stomatal resistance in order to limit water loss (Jarvis \& Davis, 1997).  
% stomatal conductance and w pot (se è basso w pot, traspiraz è molto alta --> chiusi)

\subsection{The phloem}
\subsubsection{Structure and function}
The phloem is a tissue that allows long-distance transport (translocation) of photosynthates, \textit{i.e.} the product of photosynthesis. Redistribution of water and other compounds is another one of its functions. Photosynthates must be transported from their source, typically mature leaves, to areas of growth that are unable to produce enough assimilates, such as young leaves, fruits, or roots. Storage organs, including roots, tubers and rhizomes, can be both sink, when accumulating nutrients, and source, when providing said nutrients to the plant body during winter or other stress-inducing times (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). Seeds do the same, transitioning from sink to source when they germinate, so that the resources that they accumulated as starch can be used by the new plant to grow (Rascio et al., 2017).
\smallskip

In Angiosperms, which are the main object of research on the phloem, xylem and phloem form vascular tissues that extend throughout the plant body, with the xylem being usually closer to the centre of the stem (or the root), and the phloem on the outer side (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). The two continuously exchange water. 
\smallskip

The phloem is made up of living cells belonging to three different categories: sieve elements, companion cells and parenchymatic cells. In Angiosperms, sieve elements are roughly cylinder-shaped cells that are stacked on top of each other, forming a sieve tube (Rascio et al., 2017). Cross walls separating the cells are perforated by pores (Figure \ref{fig:sieve}), forming sieve plates, to achieve symplastic continuity and a higher hydraulic conductance inside the tube (Peters \& Knoblauch, 2022). As sieve cells do not possess a nucleus, a cytoskeleton and other essential organelles, each sieve cell is associated with one or more companion cells. Plasmodesmata provide a close symplastic relationship between sieve cells and companion cells. The latter have intense metabolic activity and are responsible for the survival of the sieve cells. They also contribute to the transport of photosynthates from mesophyll cells in leaves, where they are produced, to sieve cells (Rascio et al., 2017).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth, angle=0]{images/sieve.png}
    \caption{\textit{Hypocotyl of Cucurbita maxima. Image of a longitudinal section of two sieve tube elements, taken with an electron microscope. The pores of the sieve plate are visible between the two elements. The inset shows sieve plate pores. Image taken from Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002}}
    \label{fig:sieve}
\end{figure}

Phloem sap is rich in sucrose, varying from 0.3 to 0.9 M in concentration. In addition to sucrose, the phloem of certain plant families also contains high concentrations of sugar alcohols like mannitol and carbohydrates like raffinose and stachyose. Other solutes in lower concentrations include amino acids, hormones, proteins and inorganic solutes (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). 
\smallskip

Long-distance transport in the phloem is usually explained by the pressure-flow hypothesis, formulated by Ernst Münch in the 1920s. The hypothesis states that mass flow of water and solutes in the phloem is driven by an osmotically induced pressure gradient between source and sink organs (Figure \ref{fig:munch}). The loading of photosynthates into the sieve elements at the source causes a low osmotic potential ($\Psi_s$), which in turn causes a negative water potential ($\Psi_w$), so that water is drawn into the phloem from neighboring xylem tissue and thus increase the turgor pressure near the source. The opposite phenomenon happens in the sink organs, where photoassimilates are unloaded from the sieve elements and water potential becomes more positive, leading water to leave the phloem as well and the turgor pressure to decrease. This difference in turgor pressure ($\Delta P$), which is higher at the source and lower at the sink, pushes the fluid along the phloem from source to sink (Knoblauch et al, 2016). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth, angle=0]{images/Munch_schema_tagl.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between xylem and phloem. Water enters the phloem at the source and leaves at the sink because of a water potential difference ($\Delta\Psi_w$), while source-to-sink mass flow is made possible by a difference in turgor pressure ($\Delta P$). Image taken from Rascio N. et al., 2017.}}
    \label{fig:munch}
\end{figure}

Because the phloem sap is rich in nutrients, it is very likely to be attacked by predators or parasites. Therefore, the tissue employs some strong defense mechanisms. For instance, plants use callose to occlude wounded sieve tubes and protect them from attacks (Will et al., 2013). It can be difficult to do experiments on the phloem, as the sensors that are inserted in the tree to measure phloem transport get sealed off due to the same defense mechanisms. The phloem has been called “the least understood plant tissue” due to such difficulties (Knoblauch et al, 2016). Indirect methods, such as isotope labeling, can be used instead. % labeling
% 1 species Ricinus does not do that. Slightly toxic. For most plants you need indirect methods (labeling or measuring what comes out - proxy). Few methods that are expensive. Also, it is soft, difficult to take samples. 

\subsubsection{Source-sink interrelationship} \label{sec:source}
Apart from translocation, an area of interest when studying the phloem is the source-sink interrelationship. This topic is particularly useful for a deeper understanding of carbon allocation, \textit{i.e} the regulation of the distribution of carbon among different pathways (accumulation, transport, metabolism). Starch functions as an energy reserve and is the main molecule used for accumulation, as opposed to as sucrose, which is mostly used for transport (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). Plants are able to adjust their starch and sucrose production according to different conditions. For example, if all but one soybean leaves are shaded for several days, the only source leaf experiences an increase in the rate of net photosynthesis, a decrease in starch concentration and an increase in sucrose concentration (Thorne \& Koller, 1974).
\smallskip

Carbon allocation is influenced by the communication between source and sink, namely a decreased sink demand can lead to a decrease in the speed of phloem transport and to limitations in source organ activity (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). This acclimation to changing source-sink relationships ensures a better coordination among source photosynthetic activity, phloem translocation and sink organ demand. 
\smallskip

Decreased sink demand can happen, for example, if a plant undergoes defruiting, because sink size (the total biomass of sink tissue) gets reduced. Temperature can also have an effect on sink demand by influencing sink activity (the rate of uptake of photoassimilates): if root temperature goes down, the process of respiration - which consumes the sugars produced by photosynthesis and is the main driver for root growth - decreases as well. Thus, less carbon is required for respiration and its allocation towards the roots is limited by lower temperatures (Lambers, 2008). 
Together, sink size and sink activity co-regulate sink strength, the ability of the sink organ to import photoassimilates (Balasubramanian et al., 2023).
\smallskip 

Communication between source and sink can happen through various means, including transport sugars themselves. According to this model, decreased sink demand causes high sucrose levels in the phloem, which in turn cause down-regulation of phloem loading at the source. Thus, carbohydrates accumulate in the source (mesophyll cells), which can lead to downregulation of photosynthesis (Chiou \& Bush, 1998). Generally speaking, low sugar levels cause higher photosynthetic activity, reserve mobilization and transport towards sink organs, whereas high sugar concentration encourages growth and storage, as summarized by Figure (\ref{fig:sugar}) (Rolland et al., 2002).   


\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/Source-sink.png}
    \caption{Effects of sugar on source-sink activity. Image taken from Rolland et al., 2002.}
    \label{fig:sugar}
\end{figure}


% Source-sink relationship can be explored by applying a variety of treatments, such as girdling and defruiting, to plants, and can have applications in agriculture as well, if fruits are the sink organs being studied (probably cut this).
Several studies have been performed over the years about the relationship between sink demand and photosynthetic activity. For example, in Frank et. al, 2006, the authors girdled \textit{Coffea arabica} branches at their base. Girdling is a technique where scientists remove a ring of phloem is in order to disconnect source and sink in the plant. They subsequently measured total soluble sugar concentration ($SSC_m$) and maximal leaf net $CO_2$ assimilation rate $A_{max}$ on the mature leaves of the girdled branches. The results showed that $A_{max}$ was negatively correlated to $SSC_m$, that it was higher in branches with higher fruit loads and that it decreased during the day. A conclusion was drawn that there was sink feedback down-regulating photosynthesis \textit{e.g.} low fruit loads demanded less photosynthates, therefore photosynthetic activity decreased. It was thought that the feedback is mediated by the accumulation of sugars in the leaf phloem, which inhibits phloem loading. 
\smallskip

Other similar experiments on apples trees (Wünsche et al., 2005) and peach trees (Duan \& al., 2007) provided similar results, with photosynthetic rate decreasing when the crop load was reduced or removed. Da Matta et al., 2007 proposed a different conclusion regarding their experiment on coffee: the decreased \textit{A} in the leaves of the defruited trees was thought to have been caused caused not by direct sink feedback, but by the lower stomatal conductance, as (\textit{A}) and (\textit{g}) were correlated. The reason for the lower \textit{g} remains unknown.

\subsection{Soil cooling}
Other than fruits, roots can also be studied as sink organs down-regulating photosynthesis, as this thesis will investigate. As stated in section \ref{sec:source}, cooling down the roots of a tree inhibits its sink activity. This technique is not as disruptive as girdling is: since no tissues are damaged, wound responses do not get triggered, and there is a lower risk of changes in secondary metabolism affecting the experiment. 
\smallskip

Soil cooling has been known to limit photosynthesis in several different species like \textit{Artemisia tridentata} (BassiriRad et al., 1993), pine (Day et al., 1991; Lintunen et al., 2020), aspen and spruce (Cai et al., 2001. The inhibition is thought to be caused by both stomatal and non-stomatal limitation. The latter includes mesophyll and chloroplast resistance to $CO_2$ and metabolic restrictions such as RuBiSCo inactivation (Signarbieux et al, 2010; Salmon et al., 2020). 
\smallskip

Day et al., 1991 observed that stomatal limitation may have had a major role in the decrease of net photosynthetic rate as temperature dropped from 24°C to 7°C. This is suggested by stomatal resistance and intercellular $CO_2$ concentration declining as well. At temperatures below 7°C, intercellular $CO_2$ concentration increased, but the photosynthetic rate kept decreasing, suggesting non-stomatal limitation. % does this make sense? 
\smallskip

Root cooling for \textit{Artemisia tridentata} also resulted in a limitation of photosynthesis. The A (photosynthetic rate) versus $C_i$ (intercellular $CO_2$ concentration) curve did not change with temperature, which suggests stomatal limitation (BassiriRad et al., 1993). 
\smallskip

There can be multiple causes for stomatal and non-stomatal limitation. While they might be a result of direct sink feedback and sugar accumulation, they might also be connected to a lower hydraulic conductivity. When soil temperature goes down, hydraulic conductivity has been shown to also decline. Because the roots take up water less efficiently, the water potential of the entire plant is negatively affected, and stomatal conductance ends up declining as well (Day et al., 1991; Lintunen et al., 2020). % coordination between st and non-st conductance? (other paper)

%Cooling a sink tissue inhibits activities that require metabolic energy and results in a decrease in the speed of transport toward the sink 
%list of everything that is hypothesized to happen once you cool the roots: hyd cond goes down, less water uptake, phloem transport gets slower, phot slows down due to both sink fb and lower w pot: OK

\subsection{\textit{Betula pendula}}
\textit{Betula pendula}, or European white birch, is a deciduous tree with white bark, drooping outer branches and an average height of 25 m (Vakkari P., 2009). Leaves are simple, triangular-shaped, with a dentate margin. It is a Eurosiberian tree distributed in almost all of Europe (but most abundant in Northern Europe) and many parts of Asia and North America (ref gbif website). Information on \textit{Betula pendula}'s vascular tissues (Figure \ref{fig:stem}), and on sink limitation is scarce, as studies are usually conducted on model organisms like \textit{Arabidopsis thaliana}.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.3\textwidth]{images/birch_stem.png}
    \caption{Cross section of \textit{Betula pendula}'s stem. Secondary growth with outer phloem tissue (ph), cambial zone (ca) and inner xylem (xy). Image taken from (Hellman et al., 2018).}
    \label{fig:stem}
\end{figure}

\cleardoublepage

\section{Aim of the thesis} \label{sec:aim}
The present work was conducted in the framework of Xin Zhuang’s Doctorate research. The wider scope of the experiment was a study on the effects of sink limitation on \textit{Betula pendula} source activity and carbon translocation in the phloem (Zhuang et al., in progress). This thesis focuses on part of the results, namely the effects of sink limitation on canopy photosynthesis, the hypothesis being that decreased sink activity limits source photosynthetic activity.
\smallskip
% be clear about my results vs whole experiment
Sink activity reduction was achieved by cooling the soil around the roots of 12 saplings, while 8 other trees were left untreated to function as controls. Gas exchange variables, such as $CO_2$ net assimilation rate and photosynthetic efficiency, were measured with the purpose of researching how the sink limitation created by soil cooling affected leaf photosynthetic activity. 
\smallskip

I am also reporting on the results of the water status monitoring (water potential monitoring) during the experiment. Here, soil cooling is expected to cause stress for the saplings, with less root water uptake and a decrease in water potential and stomatal conductance. The stress and the lower water uptake could also contribute to a lower stomatal conductance and lower photosynthesis, which might not be exclusively a result of direct feedback from the sink (decreased sink demand). %preliminary results
% we limit sink activity + side effect: hydraulic conductivity between root and soil (water has more trouble moving from soil to xylem) - water potential measures that (references).
\smallskip
% Is it clear how source activity/ photosynthesis and translocation/ phloem transport are connected? 


