\subsubsection{Water potential}
%what is water potential, etc from textbook
% pressure chamber is explained in Rascio, as well 
The pressure chamber (Figure \ref{fig:pressure}) is a device for measuring water potential by applying pressure to a leaf thanks to a nitrogen tank. For our experiment, two leaves were taken from each tree and inserted in the chamber one at a time, with the cut end of the stem exposed outside of it. 
Pressure was then applied until water appeared at the surface of the exposed end. This is the amount of pressure that is equal and opposite to the water potential measurement. Therefore, higher values of pressure indicate higher stress for the tree. Maximum instrument operating pressure was 100 Bar \citep{PMS_Instrument_Company_2009}.
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{images/pressure_chamber.jpg}
    \caption{\textit{Pressure chamber in the greenhouse.}}
    \label{fig:pressure}
\end{figure}

%second image?
Measurements were taken in the early afternoon to make sure they were comparable, as water potential changes during the day, usually having the most negative values at midday. For each tree, two leaves were chosen to be measured and then an average was calculated and used for further analysis.
%$ \prescript{13}{}{\(CO_2\)} $

% add temperature instrument information

\subsubsection{Isotope pulse-labeling}
 For our experiment, the labeled ${}^{13} CO_2$ was pumped into plastic bags that had been wrapped around the birches' canopy. Labeled carbon  was then traced with Picarro's G2201-i Isotopic Analyzer, as it was transported from the source (leaves) to the sink organs, via the phloem. Chambers were sealed at two different locations along the stem and connected to the analyzer, so that the carbon could be traced when it respired. The difference in time lags between the appearance of labeled C at the first and second location can be used to establish phloem sap velocity \citep{Epron_D._et_al._2019}. However, this data is still being processed by Xin Zhuang, as it requires complex analysis, therefore it will not be discussed any further in this thesis.
%image?

\subsection{Statistical analysis} \label{sec:stat}
For the statistical analysis, I used the programming language R (R Core Team, 2023).
\smallskip
% add packages used
The first part of the analysis tested whether there was a significant difference between the leaf gas exchange of cooled trees and control trees by analysing four variables: \textit{A}, \textit{$A/C_i$}, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw}. The possibility of a significant difference among the four batches had to be taken into consideration as well, as they were measured during different parts of the growing season, starting from early June and ending in mid August.
\smallskip

Employing a parametric ANOVA was not possible, as the distribution of the data was not normal nor were the residual of the ANOVA analysis. Data transformation did not solve the issue. Therefore, these data were tested for difference using the Scheirer–Ray–Hare test with a significance level of $0.05$. The Scheirer–Ray–Hare test is a non-parametric test used for a two-way factorial design (Sokal and Rohlf, 1995).    
\smallskip

An example of the code used for the this part, for the variable \textit{A}, is given below:

\begin{verbatim}
    SRH_A <- scheirerRayHare(avg.A ~ batch + treatment, 
             data=licor_avg)
\end{verbatim}

The second part of the analysis aimed at studying whether there was a significant effect of soil cooling (and soil temperature in general) on the same four gas exchange variables. $P<0.05$ was considered to be statistically significant here as well.
Because the distribution of the data as well as of the residual of the linear regression were not normal, a classical linear regression was not suitable. Instead, a generalized linear model with a gamma distribution was used for \textit{A} and \textit{$A/C_i$}. This distribution looks like a Gaussian distribution skewed to the left (Zuur et al., 2009), which is similar to how the distribution for \textit{A} values appears (Figure \ref{fig:distrib}).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A_distrib.png}
    \caption{\textit{$CO_2$ net assimilation in cooled and control trees. }}
    \label{fig:distrib}
\end{figure}

An example of the code is given below for \textit{A}:

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaA <- glm(formula = licor_avg_2$avg.A ~ 
              licor_avg_2$batch + licor_avg_2$soil_temperature,
              family = Gamma(), data = licor_avg)
\end{verbatim}

The response of the other two variables (\textit{E} and \textit{gsw}) to the soil temperature was also non-linear, even after data transformation was attempted. Therefore, the Generalized Additive Model (GAM) was employed instead of the Generalized Linear Model. The Generalized Additive Model is suitable to study non-linear relationships and fit the data better than the gamma distribution.

Here is an example for \textit{E}:

\begin{verbatim}
   gamE <- gam(licor_avg$avg.E ~ 
           s(licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, fx = FALSE, k=3, 
           bs = "cr") + s(licor_avg_2$batch, fx = FALSE, k=3, 
           bs = "cr"))
\end{verbatim}
    
The models were validated with the help of diagnostic plots (Zuur et al., 2009), as shown in Figure \ref{fig:diagnostics}, for \textit{A}. % choose just one of the four. If there was a variable that was important and we had not considered, then a pattern would appear. or model is just not caupturing data well.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/diagnostic_plot_A.png}
    \caption{\textit{Diagnostic plots for the gamma distribution model (A  soil temperature). The four plots show response residuals (observed minus fitted values), Pearson residuals, scaled Pearson residuals and deviance residuals.}}
    \label{fig:diagnostics}
\end{figure}

The data is not normally distributed, which means that the model is a good fit for the data if the diagnostic plots show a lack of pattern (Zuur, 2009). % i don't know whether to put the diagnostic plots here, because I don't understand the statistics very well (only the basics) e. g. the different residuals
\smallskip

The same models and the same validation process were chosen for the third part of the analysis, where the effect of water potential on the four gas exchange variables was examined, with the following code (for \textit{A}):

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaA2 <- glm(licor_avg$avg.A ~ 
               licor_avg_3$batch + licor_avg_3$water_potential,
               data=licor_avg_3, family=Gamma())
\end{verbatim}


\cleardoublepage

\section{Results and discussion} \label{sec:res}
This section will discuss results pertaining to batch 1, 2 and 4, whereas batch 3 will not be included due to anomalies found throughout the data analysis. 
\smallskip
% add a callback to the Aim of the thesis

\subsection{Effect of soil temperature on leaf gas exchange}
The first part of the analysis aimed at comparing the photosynthetic activity in control trees and treated trees. The four gas exchange variables measured all showed a significant difference between the two groups. A boxplot, generated using the package \texttt{ggplot2} (Wickham, 2016), was chosen to represent this difference. The box includes the values between the first and the third quartile and is divided by a line, the median. The "whiskers" show the values outside of the central 50\%. The boxplots (Figure \ref{fig:A}, Figure \ref{fig:E} and Figure \ref{fig:gsw}) show that the control trees had significantly higher values than the treated trees (p-value$<10^{-5}$). 

The median of \textit{A} values for the controls was about 9 $\mu mol m^{-2} s^{-1}$, whereas the median for the cooled trees was less than 5 $\mu mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$ (Figure \ref{fig:A}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A.png}
    \caption{\textit{$CO_2$ net assimilation in control and cooled trees. The boxplot on the left (control trees) shows significantly higher values and a higher median that the boxplot on the right (treated trees).}}
    \label{fig:A}
\end{figure}

The median of \textit{E} values for the controls is about $2x10^{-3}$ $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$, while the median for the treated trees is about $5x10^-4$ $molm^{-2}s^{-1}$ (Figure \ref{fig:E}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/E.png}
    \caption{\textit{Evapotranspiration rate in control and cooled trees.}}
    \label{fig:E}
\end{figure}

The median of \textit{gsw} values for the controls was about 0.14 $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$, whereas the median for the cooled trees was less than 0.05 $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$ (Figure \ref{fig:gsw}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/gsw.png}
    \caption{\textit{Stomatal conductance to water vapor in control and cooled trees.}}
    \label{fig:gsw}
\end{figure}

Photosynthetic efficiency was also significantly different in control trees and treated trees, however the p-value was higher (0.007). Boxplot \ref{fig:A-Ci} shows that control trees have higher values than treated trees, but the medians of the two groups are closer to one another (0.03 $mol m^{-2} s{-1}$ for the controls and about 0.02 $mol m^{-2} s{-1}$ for the treated trees). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_over_Ci.png}
    \caption{\textit{Photosynthetic efficiency in control and cooled trees.}}
    \label{fig:A-Ci}
\end{figure}

Having established that the cooled trees have significantly lower values for the gas exchange variables, the second part of the analysis adds to the first part by focusing on the impact of low soil temperatures (explanatory variable) on the leaf gas exchange variables (response variables). The impact on the four variables proved to be significant, as shown by the p-values for the slope of the model.

The relationship between \textit{A} and soil temperature had a p-value=$3x10^{-5}$ for the slope of the model. All batches show a decrease in $CO_2$ assimilation as temperature decreases (Figure \ref{fig:A2}. However, there is a significant difference among the batches, as well (p-value=0.044). In particular, batch 1 shows a steeper slope, as the \textit{A} values for control trees are higher.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A2.png}
    \caption{\textit{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on $CO_2$ assimilation. Batches 1, 2 and 4 are represented by different colors, whereas two different shapes are used for control (circle) and treated (triangle) trees. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}}
    \label{fig:A2}
\end{figure}

The relationship between \textit{$A/C_i$} and soil temperature is significant, but the p-value is higher (p=0.032), as a lot of the cooled trees have high photosynthetic efficiency values (Figure \ref{fig:A_over_Ci2}). Once again, batch 1 has a steeper slope than the other two batches (p-value=0.003).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_over_Ci2.png}
    \caption{\textit{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on photosynthetic efficiency. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}}
    \label{fig:A_over_Ci2}
\end{figure}

Soil temperature had a significant effect on \textit{E}, with a p-value$<2x10^{-16}$ (Figure \ref{fig:E2}).  

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/E2.png}
    \caption{\textit{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on the $H_2O$ evapotraspiration rate. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}}
    \label{fig:E2}
\end{figure}

The scatter plot representing the effect of soil temperature on \textit{gsw} shows a similar trend to the previous plot, with the same p-value. This is to be expected, given the close relation between the two variables. 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/gsw2.png}
    \caption{\textit{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on the stomatal conductance. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}}
    \label{fig:gsw2}
\end{figure}

These last two plots show the clearest relationship between response variable and explanatory variable and the biggest difference between control trees values and cooled trees values. The reason why batch 1 has a steeper slope and higher gas exchange values might be because it was measured earlier in the growing season, when photosynthetic activity is usually higher. % source


\subsection{Effect of water potential on leaf gas exchange}
The third part of the analysis looked at the water potential data. The hypothesis that was made in the Aim of Thesis (\ref{sec:aim}) was that hydraulic conductance, and thus water potential as well, would be negatively affected by soil cooling, showing a decrease as soil temperature dropped. In order to verify this, the effect of soil temperature on water potential was examined using a gamma distribution model. In this case, the hypothesis was proven wrong: with a p-value=0.4462, the relationship was not significant.    
\smallskip

A further analysis was made to establish whether water potential affected the four gas exchange variables. Here, the explanatory variable (water potential) had a significant impact on all four response variables: gas exchange variables increased as water potential decreased, which is an unexpected result, as lower water potential values indicates a stressed plant. %source 
The relationship between \textit{A} values and water potential can be seen in Figure \ref{fig:A3_full} (p-value=0.009 for the slope of the model).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A3_full.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between \textit{A} (response variable) and water potential (explanatory variable). $CO_2$ assimilation increases as water potential decreases.}}
    \label{fig:A3_full}
\end{figure}

A second plot (Figure \ref{fig:A3}) shows that control trees and treated trees were affected differently by the change in water potential. \textit{A} values in control trees increase significantly as water potential decreases (p-value=0.002), whereas \textit{A} values in treated trees are stable.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A3.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between \textit{A} (response variable) and water potential (explanatory variable), with a distinction made between control trees (violet) and cooled trees (yellow).}}
    \label{fig:A3}
\end{figure}

Similar results can be found for \textit{E} values (Figure \ref{fig:E3} and \textit{gsw} values (Figure \ref{fig:gsw3}), which both increase significantly as water potential decreases (p-value are 0.008 and 0.004, respectively). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/E3.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between \textit{E} (response variable) and water potential (explanatory variable), with a distinction made between control trees (violet) and cooled trees (yellow).}}
    \label{fig:E3}
\end{figure}


\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/gsw3.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between \textit{gsw} (response variable) and water potential (explanatory variable), with a distinction made between control trees (violet) and cooled trees (yellow).}}
    \label{fig:gsw3}
\end{figure}

Finally, the plot representing the effect of water potential on photosynthetic efficiency shows a decrease of $A/C_i$ as water potential decreases, however only the slope for the control trees is significant (p-value=0.006). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A_over_Ci3.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between \textit{$A/C_i$} (response variable) and water potential (explanatory variable), with a distinction made between control trees (violet) and cooled trees (yellow).}}
    \label{fig:A_over_Ci3}
\end{figure}

The results for the third part of the analysis are difficult to explain, as they contradict the initial hypothesis. It is possible that another factor that was not taken into consideration might have had an impact on the control trees (but not on the cooled trees), causing the increase of the gas exchange values and/ or interacting with the water potential. % rewrite

